WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.490 --> 00:00:03.600
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Thank you
everybody for coming.

00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:07.640
I'm very pleased to have John
Wood here, who is the founder

00:00:07.640 --> 00:00:13.850
of Room to Read and author of
two books, "Leaving Microsoft

00:00:13.850 --> 00:00:17.700
to Change the World," which he
came to Google before and

00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:23.950
spoke for a book tour, and
for his latest book.

00:00:23.950 --> 00:00:27.790
"Leaving Room to Read." We have
copies in the back for

00:00:27.790 --> 00:00:31.370
all of you who want to
get your own version.

00:00:31.370 --> 00:00:35.910
But I was very excited to have
John here because Room to Read

00:00:35.910 --> 00:00:40.170
has been a charity that I have
personally supported.

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:45.200
And I think he's done some
really amazing things.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:48.290
So as he mentioned in
his title his book,

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:50.430
he did leave Microsoft.

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:53.890
He did change the world in
a lot of different ways.

00:00:53.890 --> 00:01:01.470
And in just 10 years, he has
opened up 1,6000 schools,

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:04.720
15,000 libraries.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.235
He has distributed 12 million
books, and he has reached 7.8

00:01:09.235 --> 00:01:11.800
million children.

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:16.240
And he works in Bangladesh,
Cambodia, India, Laos, Nepal,

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:20.750
South Africa, Sri Lanka,
Tanzania, Vietnam, and Zambia.

00:01:20.750 --> 00:01:25.210
So that's a really impressive
list of accomplishments.

00:01:25.210 --> 00:01:30.420
And John wound of doing
this somewhat by--

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:32.070
I don't know if it's
by accident.

00:01:32.070 --> 00:01:33.340
But I'd like John to come up.

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:35.060
And I'm going to ask him some
questions about his

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:36.450
story and this book.

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:39.640
And then I'll open it up
to the rest of you

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.780
to hear your questions.

00:01:41.780 --> 00:01:44.670
So let's welcome John.

00:01:50.371 --> 00:01:52.045
JOHN WOOD: It's always amazing
how nobody wants to

00:01:52.045 --> 00:01:52.940
sit in front row.

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:53.260
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Yeah.

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.960
JOHN WOOD: There's always empty
chairs in the rows.

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:56.920
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Yeah,
I was gonna--

00:01:56.920 --> 00:01:57.880
JOHN WOOD: There we got one.

00:01:57.880 --> 00:01:59.910
We got at least taker.

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:00.830
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Yes,
at least one taker.

00:02:00.830 --> 00:02:02.490
And future people will come.

00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:03.900
We'll have them sit
in the front too.

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:04.580
JOHN WOOD: OK.

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:06.270
SUSAN WOJCICKI: We'll call them
out as soon as they come

00:02:06.270 --> 00:02:08.704
in the back door, to come
into the front.

00:02:08.704 --> 00:02:10.250
Oh look, more people
in the front.

00:02:10.250 --> 00:02:10.670
JOHN WOOD: Yeah.

00:02:10.670 --> 00:02:14.350
Sit in the front row.

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:17.480
SUSAN WOJCICKI: So let's maybe
just start from the

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.430
beginning, if we can.

00:02:20.430 --> 00:02:23.410
JOHN WOOD: I was
born-- no, no.

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:25.200
SUSAN WOJCICKI: So this happens
to me too, if you ask

00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:26.080
me to repeat my story.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:27.475
But it is really interesting.

00:02:27.475 --> 00:02:32.780
And I'd like everyone to hear
how is it that you wound up

00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:34.300
like being at Microsoft?

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:36.370
Similar to probably a lot of
people here in the room, you

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:41.420
were a marketing manager for
APAC at Microsoft, thinking

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:43.550
about changing the world
with software.

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:47.490
And then all of a sudden,
something happened and your

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:49.660
life took a totally
different course.

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:50.230
JOHN WOOD: Yeah.

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:52.280
I joined Microsoft in 1991.

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:56.050
I was two years out of grad
school, did my MBA.

00:02:56.050 --> 00:02:57.340
Really had no business
being there.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:02:58.890
I don't know if any of you over
wake up in the morning

00:02:58.890 --> 00:03:00.960
and you kind of feel like oh my
gosh, like I really don't

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:04.260
know that I really belong in
this hypersmart environment.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:05.860
I definitely felt that
way when I joined

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:07.430
Microsoft in '91.

00:03:07.430 --> 00:03:10.650
And by '98, I was a little
bit burned out.

00:03:10.650 --> 00:03:11.800
You know the whole seven
year itch thing.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.750
After seven years of way too
many meetings and way too many

00:03:16.750 --> 00:03:19.080
flights and stuff like that, I
decided off to Nepal and do an

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:22.000
18 day trek, just kind of clear
my head and get away

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.070
from it all, the Annapurna
circuit.

00:03:23.070 --> 00:03:25.010
There was actually a rumor that
if you went high enough

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:26.570
in the Himalayas you could
escape the sound of Steve

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:29.600
Balmer's voice.

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:31.820
And I decided to give
that a shot.

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:33.793
No, I loved working for Steve.

00:03:33.793 --> 00:03:35.460
I learned a lot under him.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:39.740
But when I was on day two of
my trek, I met a headmaster

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.350
who wanted to show
me his school.

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:45.070
It was a really ramshackle,
dilapidated school, dirt

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:48.376
floors, no desks, 80 children
crammed in a room that

00:03:48.376 --> 00:03:50.000
probably should not
held more than 20.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.880
And then he said, well come and
see the school's library.

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.630
And I thought, oh, this will
be the exciting, optimistic

00:03:54.630 --> 00:03:55.110
part of the tour.

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:57.330
How many of you were library
nerds as kids?

00:03:57.330 --> 00:03:58.550
You work at Google,
so that's probably

00:03:58.550 --> 00:04:00.370
a fairly safe question.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:02.560
So I was like a total library
nerd as a kid.

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:04.970
So I thought this will be the
exciting part of the tour,

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:06.960
kids with smiles on their
faces, reading books.

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:10.660
Eh, totally wrong, empty room,
completely devoid of

00:04:10.660 --> 00:04:11.470
children's books.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:13.090
And I asked the head master,
how can this be?

00:04:13.090 --> 00:04:14.300
You have 450 kids showing up.

00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:17.279
They want to learn and their
parents want them to learn.

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:20.220
And the headmaster said, well
in Nepal we're too poor to

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:21.540
afford education.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:25.600
But until we have education,
we will always remain poor.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:28.020
And that just hit me like a
ton of bricks as being the

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:30.765
cruelest possible Catch-22 that
you have these kids who

00:04:30.765 --> 00:04:33.810
are five years old, or six years
old, or seven years old,

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:36.310
and they're being told you've
lost the lottery of life.

00:04:36.310 --> 00:04:38.680
And thankfully, the headmaster,
like me, was an

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:39.750
action-oriented optimist.

00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:43.100
He said perhaps sir, you will
someday come back with books.

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:46.130
And I thought this would be a
great reason to make an annual

00:04:46.130 --> 00:04:48.850
leave from Microsoft and come
back to Nepal and trek.

00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:51.590
So I was like, yup, kind of
selfish motivation to sign up.

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:53.420
But I'm kind of joking a little
bit about the self

00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:54.346
motivation.

00:04:54.346 --> 00:04:57.110
But I grew up in a town,
small town, that

00:04:57.110 --> 00:04:57.960
was very middle class.

00:04:57.960 --> 00:04:59.950
We have a great school library
and we had a great community

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:01.610
library that had been
built in 1896.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:03.430
So I thought well, here's
my pay it forward.

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:06.235
I'll thank the world for my
libraries, with one library.

00:05:06.235 --> 00:05:08.440
And didn't realize we wouldn't
really stop there.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:12.870
But I went back a year later
with 3,000 donated books on

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:16.060
the back of six rented donkeys,
and my 73-year-old

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:18.130
father in tow as my unpaid
right-hand man.

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:19.200
And it just felt really good.

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:20.280
And I said well, that was fun.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:22.050
Like maybe we'll
keep doing it.

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:23.840
And that was the point
of departure.

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:27.420
It was that trip in '99
returning and seeing the

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:29.305
smiles on faces of the kids who
had never seen brightly

00:05:29.305 --> 00:05:31.170
colored children's
books before.

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:33.920
The library shelves were
suddenly full.

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:36.130
And that's the moment I started
to kind of edge my way

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.960
to the door of Microsoft, to
think maybe my next act will

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:40.010
not be in tech.

00:05:40.010 --> 00:05:43.190
Maybe it will be in something
a bit more basic.

00:05:43.190 --> 00:05:45.250
SUSAN WOJCICKI: It's like you
read the numbers here and you

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:47.830
think like 7.8 million
children whose

00:05:47.830 --> 00:05:49.320
lives you've touched.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:53.050
Like do you have any stories
or like kids that really

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:56.560
touched you in particular, like
you saw them, you saw

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:58.430
they learned something,
you saw that they got

00:05:58.430 --> 00:05:59.680
access to this book?

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:00.120
JOHN WOOD: Yeah.

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:02.890
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I mean like what
is that experience for

00:06:02.890 --> 00:06:06.690
like one of the 7.8 million kids
and how does it really

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:08.795
change their life, to
be able to have the

00:06:08.795 --> 00:06:09.840
books and the libraries?

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:10.640
JOHN WOOD: Yeah.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:12.960
It's pretty amazing to me these
kids, I hope one day all

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:15.250
of you get a chance, including
you, you're always welcome to

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:16.840
come visit our projects.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:20.000
With 1,600 schools and 15,000
libraries, there's lots of

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.500
places to go visit and meet the
kids and meet the-- not

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:25.930
just kids, but the parents and
the grandparents, whose lives

00:06:25.930 --> 00:06:26.865
are being changed.

00:06:26.865 --> 00:06:28.130
And I'll tell you a story
about a student.

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:30.360
But first I'll you a story about
being in Nepal with a

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:32.610
number of our chapter leaders
who are running fundraising

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:33.560
chapters all of the world.

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:34.440
We're very entrepreneurial.

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:37.570
So we've actually given birth
to 57 fundraising chapters

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:40.660
around the world, 12,000
people involved.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:43.270
They have not quit their day
job to change the world.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:44.350
They've kept their day job.

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:46.660
But they're changing the world
through raising funds for Room

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:49.580
to Read, including our San
Francisco chapter.

00:06:49.580 --> 00:06:52.980
But the Tokyo chapter co-founder
Susan Lodge was

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:54.580
with me on this trip.

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:57.550
And Susan told a story about
being in a village where we

00:06:57.550 --> 00:06:59.380
had a lot of girls
in our long-term

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:01.110
girls education program.

00:07:01.110 --> 00:07:03.740
And as you and I both know from
our discussions, it's

00:07:03.740 --> 00:07:05.640
depressingly inexpensive
to change a girl's

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:06.640
like through education.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.300
It's $250 per girl, per year.

00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:11.120
And so the fact that over
100 million girls in the

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:13.640
developing world woke up this
morning and not go to school

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.530
is to me just an absolutely
avoidable tragedy because it's

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:18.540
not an expensive
problem to fix.

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:20.920
But Susan said to me, John,
you've got me, Room to Read's

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.840
got me forever because I just
was talking a grandmother.

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:26.290
And she was holding my hand and
with tears in her eyes she

00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:30.510
said, I can die now that I know
that my granddaughter is

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:32.510
going to get educated.

00:07:32.510 --> 00:07:34.270
And Susan said you know,
you got a fan for life.

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:35.650
So there's a grandmother.

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:37.290
We watch parents.

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:39.330
And everything we do at Room to
Read is under a challenge

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:39.850
grant model.

00:07:39.850 --> 00:07:41.870
The idea is you can't help
people if they don't want to

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:43.110
help themselves.

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.600
So we don't go into a village
and build them a library or

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:46.620
build them a school.

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:50.260
Hey, step aside local people,
we're here to help you.

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.620
We say we're going to help you,
but only if you want to

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:53.300
help yourself.

00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:56.120
So the parents will put in sweat
equity to each project.

00:07:56.120 --> 00:07:58.715
So I've watched these parents at
school openings, at library

00:07:58.715 --> 00:08:01.680
openings, where the mothers will
come up and say, they'll

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:03.130
point down to the river.

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:05.110
That's a pretty steep decline.

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:08.270
And they'll say, I carried the
sandbags from the river up.

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:09.830
And then other parents, their
fathers will say, well I

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:10.805
helped to dig the foundation.

00:08:10.805 --> 00:08:13.180
So It's very much of
a self-help model.

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:14.620
And those parents motivate me.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:16.020
Because parents everywhere
are the same.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:18.320
They want their kids to have a
better life than they've had.

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:20.290
And it almost always
comes to education.

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:22.110
If you only bequeath one thing
to your child, you probably

00:08:22.110 --> 00:08:24.330
would want to bequeath
education.

00:08:24.330 --> 00:08:26.230
But to land the plane, your
question with the students,

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:28.260
one of my favorite stories of
a student I met with last

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:32.000
summer, my father decided for
his 86th birthday, he wanted

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.299
to go to Zambia with me on
a trip that I was doing.

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:35.470
And I love my parents.

00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:37.700
They're such adventurous
people.

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:41.604
And we are in this little
village in rural Zambia.

00:08:41.604 --> 00:08:43.140
And met a kid named Girus.

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:46.760
He's a 13-year-old student
and really well read.

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:48.660
He has a Room to Read library
in his school.

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:51.095
And he was very articulate in
welcoming me to the library.

00:08:51.095 --> 00:08:53.620
And officially, he was like
the head of the welcoming

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:55.650
committee that welcoming
our delegation.

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:56.580
And I talked to him at first.

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:59.610
I said Girus, you seem like
a very smart young man.

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:03.030
And he said, yes.

00:09:03.030 --> 00:09:06.000
And so what would you like
to be when you grow up?

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.290
And Girus said, oh, I will be
the first Zambian to be

00:09:09.290 --> 00:09:12.500
Secretary General of
United Nations.

00:09:12.500 --> 00:09:13.890
And I said OK, that's great.

00:09:13.890 --> 00:09:15.690
So you're learning a lot in your
library about leadership.

00:09:15.690 --> 00:09:18.500
And he said yes, but I've also
learned that I will have to do

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:19.800
other things along the way.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:22.160
That will not be my first job.

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:25.000
I said OK, what would be like
an interim kind of lily pad

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.830
you would jump to on the way
to that side of the pond?

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:32.550
And he, said well I will first
be president of Zambia.

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:34.700
And it's kind of funny
story, right?

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:36.800
So this was in July,
last summer.

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:39.500
Well in October, a couple months
later, at the United

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:42.540
Nations, I was a guest of Gordon
Brown, who's running

00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:46.020
this amazing Education First
initiative for Ban Ki-moon.

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:48.990
And Ban Ki-moon was telling a
story about growing up in

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:51.650
post-war South Korea in a
village that had been

00:09:51.650 --> 00:09:53.140
decimated by the war.

00:09:53.140 --> 00:09:54.570
They were learning outside.

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:57.880
The teacher had a stick, was
drawing in the dirt.

00:09:57.880 --> 00:09:59.240
That was their chalkboard.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:00.610
They had no books.

00:10:00.610 --> 00:10:04.040
And Ban Ki-moon said then one
day, these books showed up.

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:05.040
And we were really excited.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:06.650
And my parents said to me,
you must read every

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:07.420
one of those books.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:09.840
And he said we opened them up,
on the inside front cover it

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:14.810
says, "A Gift, From The United
Nations." Anybody getting

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:17.860
chills now, just thinking about
that fact that the kid

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:21.180
in the village with the stick
and the dirt and donated books

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:23.650
is now Secretary General
of the United Nations.

00:10:23.650 --> 00:10:25.930
So I don't think Girus's story
is really that far-fetched.

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:29.070
And when I think of it, I think
about one of my heroes,

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:30.800
Nelson Mandela.

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:33.520
What would South Africa look
like today had Nelson Mandela

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:36.840
not been one of the lucky few
black South African kids to

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:38.450
get educated in that era?

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:40.950
What if Wangari Maathai
had not had education.

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:42.293
The Green Belt movement in East

00:10:42.293 --> 00:10:43.080
Africa would not happened.

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:45.060
All these kids are out there.

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:47.310
We're all born with the
same gray matter.

00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:49.170
So if we can just reach them at
a young age, I think those

00:10:49.170 --> 00:10:52.730
Girus stories, I mean Girus
could be the next Ban Ki-moon.

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:56.460
We'll never know, we'll never
know unless we try to reach

00:10:56.460 --> 00:10:57.460
every one of them.

00:10:57.460 --> 00:10:59.840
If we don't reach them, we
know it won't happen.

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:01.610
But if we don't try,
we'll never know.

00:11:01.610 --> 00:11:03.406
SUSAN WOJCICKI: So is that a
goal of yours, to reach every

00:11:03.406 --> 00:11:04.380
one of them?

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.380
JOHN WOOD: Ultimately, yes.

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:07.480
Yeah.

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:10.370
I mean not just Room to Read,
I mean the greatest things

00:11:10.370 --> 00:11:11.255
that happen in human
history happen

00:11:11.255 --> 00:11:12.470
when there's a movement.

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:14.240
But movements have to have--
you got to have

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:15.980
the lead sled dogs.

00:11:15.980 --> 00:11:18.680
You got to have like a lot of
sled dogs to pull the sled.

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:20.170
But we hoped to be one of
the lead sled dogs.

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:24.390
And our interim goal was
originally to reach 10 million

00:11:24.390 --> 00:11:27.240
children across the poorest
parts of the world by 2020.

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:29.170
As you know, because I know
you read all the investor

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:31.750
reports we send you diligently,
we're actually on

00:11:31.750 --> 00:11:33.190
track to reach 10 million
children five

00:11:33.190 --> 00:11:35.140
years early, by 2015.

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:40.030
And to be clear, we're not a
movement of billionaires.

00:11:40.030 --> 00:11:40.640
They're welcome.

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.730
But we're not a top-down
model.

00:11:44.730 --> 00:11:47.100
We don't have no celebrities
involved.

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:49.260
But it's just ordinary,
average people

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:50.240
who are coming together.

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:51.900
And we've reached 7 abd 1/2
million kids already.

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:54.940
We'll reach 10 million
kids by 2015.

00:11:54.940 --> 00:11:58.240
And then from there, I want to
start sentences with the words

00:11:58.240 --> 00:11:59.480
"every child."

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:01.240
Every child gets a
chance to read.

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:03.940
Every child gets a
habit of reading.

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:07.290
Every girl child gets to go to
school, alongside the boys.

00:12:07.290 --> 00:12:09.270
Because in the developing world
today, about 40% of

00:12:09.270 --> 00:12:11.330
girls don't go to school.

00:12:11.330 --> 00:12:12.390
And that's just a shame.

00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:15.730
So ultimately, we want to
reverse the notion that any

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:17.500
child can ever be told again,
you were born in the wrong

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:20.800
place, at the wrong time, to
the wrong parents, and you

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:21.850
therefore did not
get educated.

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:25.250
We think that notion belongs in
the scrap heap of history.

00:12:25.250 --> 00:12:27.550
It might take 30 or 40 years
to get it there.

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.410
But boy, if we could do that,
that's like the whole

00:12:29.410 --> 00:12:31.620
Archimedes, give me a lever long
enough and I can move the

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:35.180
Earth, that would be I
think Earth moving.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.195
Will be, will be Earth moving.

00:12:37.195 --> 00:12:37.330
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Definitely.

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:37.895
No, it will.

00:12:37.895 --> 00:12:39.145
It definitely will.

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:43.650
So I understand you started one

00:12:43.650 --> 00:12:45.860
school sort of by accident.

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:46.570
You went there.

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:47.930
You thought though like well,
I'll just go there on my

00:12:47.930 --> 00:12:49.190
annual trek.

00:12:49.190 --> 00:12:57.150
But then you actually wound up
creating 1,600 schools and

00:12:57.150 --> 00:12:58.850
15,000 libraries.

00:12:58.850 --> 00:13:00.040
So how did that happen?

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.620
How did it happen that you
went from one to a lot?

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:05.750
And maybe tell us a little
about scaling?

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:07.720
Like at Google, we're really
good about scale.

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:09.450
And I think one of the things
that's really impressive about

00:13:09.450 --> 00:13:11.620
you is you've been able to take
something that you did

00:13:11.620 --> 00:13:13.970
once and actually scale
it many, many times.

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:15.970
So how did that happen?

00:13:15.970 --> 00:13:17.370
JOHN WOOD: I think that to
really explain it I have to

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:19.910
make sure I just use the word
"we" as I often as I can.

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:21.590
Because I've always said I don't
want to be the leader of

00:13:21.590 --> 00:13:22.840
an organization.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:24.240
I want to be one of
many, many, many

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:26.080
leaders of a global movement.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:30.490
So that requires you to A,
hire smart; B, recruit

00:13:30.490 --> 00:13:33.340
volunteers in a really,
really smart manner.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:35.180
Delegate, delegate,
delegate, right.

00:13:35.180 --> 00:13:38.360
Founders have a duty to get out
of the way with certain

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:40.150
things that they do well
and don't do well.

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:41.890
And if you ask one of my team,
they can probably give you a

00:13:41.890 --> 00:13:45.690
really long list of the stuff
that I don't do very well.

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:48.430
One thing that I happen to do
well, according to my board,

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:49.730
is I'm a good rainmaker.

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:51.660
And they think I'm a decent
public speaker and they think

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:52.990
I'm pretty good with
the media.

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:55.220
So about five years ago, I faced
the choice of do you

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:59.460
want to be CEO or do you want to
backfill that position and

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:01.070
go be a full-time ambassador?

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:04.710
And I write in the book about
that because no founder's

00:14:04.710 --> 00:14:07.930
journey is done until they
actually kind of extract

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:09.920
themselves from that position.

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:11.600
And so that was for
me, a tough thing.

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:14.360
But one of my mentors, a banker
Goldman Sachs, he said

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:16.820
look, the minute you're not CEO,
what are you going to do?

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:18.370
It's like you're going to get
your butt on a plane, you're

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:19.520
going to fly around the world.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:20.960
You're going to raise money,
you're going to speak, you're

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:22.410
going to raise money, and
you're going to speak.

00:14:22.410 --> 00:14:24.600
And the Earth's is going to spin
faster, the more times

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.720
you can circle it, telling the
Room to Read story and

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:28.990
encouraging people
to get involved.

00:14:28.990 --> 00:14:32.980
So I think for me, we have a
great CEO, Erin Ganju, like

00:14:32.980 --> 00:14:35.570
me, a business person,
ex-Goldman, ex-Unilever, a

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:36.620
brilliant woman.

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:38.050
She's hired out a
management team.

00:14:38.050 --> 00:14:40.560
So we can get a lot more
done because of that.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.970
But I think for us, a lot
of it was just kind of--

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:45.290
it's like a law of
just compounding.

00:14:45.290 --> 00:14:48.050
We said, let's do 10 libraries
our second year, then let's

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:50.070
try to do 40, and let's
try to do 100, and

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.240
let's try to do 1,000.

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:54.010
I don't know that there's
any secret sauce to it.

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:56.120
A lot of it for us is
just the execution.

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:59.510
A lot of it is not being shy
about asking for funding.

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:02.460
Because I mean how many of you
know an NGO that you love

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:04.940
that's perpetually cash
strapped like

00:15:04.940 --> 00:15:06.270
every one of us, right?

00:15:06.270 --> 00:15:09.750
So a lot the NGO world, I think
they treat fundraising

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:11.830
as kind of a dirty little side
business that they have to be

00:15:11.830 --> 00:15:13.160
kind of embarrassed about.

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:14.070
And we're not at all.

00:15:14.070 --> 00:15:15.880
I love going out and
telling people--

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:16.450
Katie's here.

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:18.320
When Katie was at the University
of Miami and they

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:21.520
me had come speak, Miami of
Ohio, the colder, but better

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:25.290
Miami, no offense to
our friends in

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:28.230
Florida, but I love them.

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:30.770
And as I said to the students,
you guys if you want, you can

00:15:30.770 --> 00:15:32.180
build a school in Nepal
and go visit it.

00:15:32.180 --> 00:15:34.320
It only costs $35,000.

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:35.560
And there was some kind
of nervous chuckling.

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:39.190
I go start with the alums, start
with the professors,

00:15:39.190 --> 00:15:40.230
start there.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.260
And within like, I don't know, a
three weeks. they had raised

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:43.290
money to build a school.

00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:44.810
And that was $35,000.

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:45.880
And they're really
proud of that.

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:47.330
And hopefully that's going to
continue a tradition year

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:48.570
after year after year.

00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:52.460
But I go to technology
conferences, I go to

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:54.350
investment banking conferences,
and I say every

00:15:54.350 --> 00:15:57.295
one of you in this room who is
educated, you would not be you

00:15:57.295 --> 00:15:57.990
without education.

00:15:57.990 --> 00:15:59.160
I would not be me.

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:00.950
This is a chance to
pay it forward.

00:16:00.950 --> 00:16:03.700
$5,000 for a classroom library,
or $35,000 for a

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:07.320
school, or $250 for a girl
to go to school.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:10.290
We've just got really good
at kind of productizing,

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:12.770
pitching, and we pitch
persistently.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:16.260
SUSAN WOJCICKI: When
we talked, I was

00:16:16.260 --> 00:16:17.120
impressed about the data.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.120
And how like you use data and
you've taken a lot of things

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:22.900
that you've learned from like
running in a business world

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:25.530
and apply that to schools.

00:16:25.530 --> 00:16:28.350
Like you told me some statistics
about like well if

00:16:28.350 --> 00:16:32.720
the girl lives like this far
away, then like this much cost

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:34.450
for her bicycle or this much--

00:16:34.450 --> 00:16:36.770
so maybe you can tell us a
little bit like data and how

00:16:36.770 --> 00:16:39.040
you guys use that?

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:40.860
We're also a very data
driven company.

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:45.520
And it's interesting to see
how you've applied this to

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:47.980
building schools globally.

00:16:47.980 --> 00:16:49.920
JOHN WOOD: I am a very big
believer from my time in

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:52.310
business that what gets
measured gets done.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:54.760
I know I'm preaching to the
choir here on that one.

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:57.890
So we try to measure every
single thing we do.

00:16:57.890 --> 00:16:58.420
And we're fortunate--

00:16:58.420 --> 00:16:58.860
SUSAN WOJCICKI: It
sounds familiar.

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:00.870
JOHN WOOD: --that we have
some great supporters

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:01.340
who helps us do it.

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:05.069
The Gates Foundation funds
all of our evaluations,

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:07.910
cross-program, cross-country,
under a six year grant.

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:11.150
So we can hire independent
outside evaluators.

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:12.839
You want to have independent
evaluators, right?

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:14.720
Because those evaluators should
not be on your org

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:15.654
chart, reporting in to you.

00:17:15.654 --> 00:17:17.510
The should be independent
outsiders.

00:17:17.510 --> 00:17:19.240
They go out and they make
random, unannounced spot

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:22.680
checks on our facilities
and they collect data.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:24.605
Is there a checkout system
in place in the library?

00:17:24.605 --> 00:17:25.800
Are kids using it?

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:27.700
How many books are going
home with the kids?

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:31.000
We do samples in the places
where we do literacy training,

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.900
assessments to see sample
schools which doe have a Room

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:35.863
to Read library versus the
schools that do have a Room to

00:17:35.863 --> 00:17:36.260
Read library.

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:38.470
We just got a report last
week from Bangladesh.

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:41.440
And you look at number of words
per minute a child can

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:45.010
read, control school, a
Room to Read school.

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:46.080
Well, OK that's great.

00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:46.550
They're reading lots of words.

00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:47.460
Do they comprehend?

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:49.170
So you ask them some
comprehension questions.

00:17:49.170 --> 00:17:51.490
How do they score at the control
schools, how do they

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:53.690
score at the Room
to Read schools?

00:17:53.690 --> 00:17:56.070
Girls' education, we look at
the percentage of girls who

00:17:56.070 --> 00:17:58.950
passed to the next grade every
year, a very simple assessment

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:00.440
of whether it's working
or not.

00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:04.030
But if you think about this for
a minute, if you're born a

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:08.500
girl who's poor, in a rural
village, in one of the world's

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:11.590
50 poorest countries, to
uneducated parents, you have

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:12.640
five strikes against you.

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:15.070
The world would expect
you to fail.

00:18:15.070 --> 00:18:17.440
Yet, two years ago,
97% of our girls

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:18.700
passed to the next grade.

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:22.040
Last year it was 96% We went out
and did a survey last year

00:18:22.040 --> 00:18:23.960
to figure out what percentage of
the girls who had finished

00:18:23.960 --> 00:18:26.250
secondary school, like what
are they doing now?

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:27.120
They finished secondary
school.

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:27.500
That's great.

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:28.530
Now, what are they doing?

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:32.230
We found that 64% of them are
now enrolled in university or

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:33.930
tertiary education.

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:37.010
That is a rate of attainment
higher than some schools in

00:18:37.010 --> 00:18:38.110
the developed world.

00:18:38.110 --> 00:18:40.280
And to be clear, we're not
saying congratulations.

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:41.650
You've graduated secondary
school.

00:18:41.650 --> 00:18:43.270
Here's your Room to Read
college scholarship.

00:18:43.270 --> 00:18:46.640
We're saying congratulations,
you're on our own.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:47.130
Good luck.

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:49.860
Find a government scholarship
scheme, work by day, go to

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:52.120
school by night or vice versa.

00:18:52.120 --> 00:18:54.950
And we work with these girls on
their life skills to give

00:18:54.950 --> 00:18:55.440
them the confidence.

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:57.080
So they're going and they're
applying for these

00:18:57.080 --> 00:18:57.640
scholarships.

00:18:57.640 --> 00:18:58.840
So they're working.

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:00.040
And they're are in school.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:02.330
And I think great because as we
know, that's how a middle

00:19:02.330 --> 00:19:06.300
class begins to form, when not
just boys, but also when girls

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:09.910
get educated and go
on to university.

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:12.140
AUDIENCE: But all of your
schools are co-ed.

00:19:12.140 --> 00:19:12.870
Is that right?

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:13.170
JOHN WOOD: Yes.

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:14.460
SUSAN WOJCICKI: So maybe you can
tell us a little bit about

00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:18.830
philosophy there and why you
think that's so important?

00:19:18.830 --> 00:19:20.160
JOHN WOOD: I think that if look
at the world today and

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:23.350
you look at a situation like
Malawa's in Pakistan where

00:19:23.350 --> 00:19:26.380
girls are being harassed or shot
for going to school or

00:19:26.380 --> 00:19:28.600
you look at places in the
world where people are

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:32.790
throwing acid on girls, and just
really bad stuff happens

00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:34.590
all throughout the world.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:37.570
And my own personal belief is
that a lot of the reason for

00:19:37.570 --> 00:19:39.720
that is that boys and girls
just don't go to

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:40.850
school side by side.

00:19:40.850 --> 00:19:43.840
They don't grow up in
relatively normal

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:46.470
circumstances where boys and
girls are in the classroom

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:48.610
together from kindergarten
through grade one, through

00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:50.130
grade two, through
grade three.

00:19:50.130 --> 00:19:52.810
And so the boys haven't really
seen the girls achieve

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:53.255
academically.

00:19:53.255 --> 00:19:56.740
And when all these girls are
not in school, well then

00:19:56.740 --> 00:19:59.430
society starts to really devalue
the women and the

00:19:59.430 --> 00:20:00.620
girls because they didn't
go to school.

00:20:00.620 --> 00:20:02.290
And I think we have to
not just change--

00:20:02.290 --> 00:20:05.340
this whole thing about women's
empowerment, it can't be a

00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:07.390
women's issue.

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:09.520
Men, we've got to
enlist in this

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:11.580
battle for gender equality.

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:13.360
Not just because it's the
right thing to do.

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:14.930
I think it was Hillary Clinton
that said it's

00:20:14.930 --> 00:20:15.740
not a women's issue.

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:16.990
It's a human rights issue.

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:22.720
I know for myself if somebody
ever came up to me and said,

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:25.740
women are dumb, women are
inferior, I would have all

00:20:25.740 --> 00:20:29.680
this case data to reject that
notion, my educated

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:32.550
grandmother, who read to me,
God bless her; my educated

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:36.940
mother; my educated older
sister; all the girls in my

00:20:36.940 --> 00:20:39.275
school who kicked my butt
academically and

00:20:39.275 --> 00:20:40.670
were top of the class.

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:43.270
I don't think that boys and
girls going to school, as

00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:45.860
somebody said, is going to solve
every single problem.

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:49.520
But I think if you actually have
that be the new normal

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:53.150
from age five, that's going to
do a lot to take these forces

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:57.420
of misogyny and these forces of
sexism and turn them around

00:20:57.420 --> 00:20:59.185
in a really, really
significant way.

00:20:59.185 --> 00:21:03.040
SUSAN WOJCICKI: And now that
there's the internet, how do

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:07.360
you think that's going to change
books ands libraries

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:11.540
for schools globally?

00:21:11.540 --> 00:21:14.660
I mean you could imagine
it could be easier.

00:21:14.660 --> 00:21:16.310
You just like download
the books.

00:21:16.310 --> 00:21:19.360
You don't actually have
to ship them anymore.

00:21:19.360 --> 00:21:21.670
I mean do you see like a world
where you're actually

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:25.230
installing digital libraries in
all of these locations and

00:21:25.230 --> 00:21:28.510
like just getting files?

00:21:28.510 --> 00:21:30.130
JOHN WOOD: I think in the
medium term, yes.

00:21:30.130 --> 00:21:33.250
I think in a short term, there's
a risk really of

00:21:33.250 --> 00:21:35.150
putting the cart before
the horse.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:38.130
And also different things are
going to work in different

00:21:38.130 --> 00:21:39.650
places based upon
circumstances.

00:21:39.650 --> 00:21:41.220
You look at something like Khan

00:21:41.220 --> 00:21:44.050
Academy, absolutely fantastic.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:46.783
But there's certain
preconditions you have to have

00:21:46.783 --> 00:21:47.920
to actually have
that be useful.

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:49.880
Like it helps to have
electricity.

00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:51.630
And it helps to have a computer
and it helps to have

00:21:51.630 --> 00:21:54.950
broadband and it helps
to be literate.

00:21:54.950 --> 00:21:57.640
So what Room to Read is doing
is a lot of the stuff we're

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:01.110
doing is kind of the really
early stage foundational stuff

00:22:01.110 --> 00:22:05.650
of saying let's get kids from
grade one to have really well

00:22:05.650 --> 00:22:07.040
trained teachers.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:09.650
Because at the end of the day,
you want your kids to have

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:10.670
good teachers.

00:22:10.670 --> 00:22:12.820
Let's have them have
well-stocked libraries.

00:22:12.820 --> 00:22:14.550
Let's have literature in
the mother tongue.

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:17.650
Because publishers don't publish
books in languages

00:22:17.650 --> 00:22:18.960
read by predominantly
poor people.

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:21.200
We should talk about
that a little bit.

00:22:21.200 --> 00:22:24.430
And the reality is for us is
we can open a library for

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:26.940
about $5,000.

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:28.960
The average library serves
400 children.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:33.140
So you're looking at a cost of
$12.50 per child reached.

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:34.510
So the low-tech solution is

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:36.740
actually really cost effective.

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:40.000
Books don't need
to be rebooted.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.750
Books don't have operating
systems that degrade.

00:22:42.750 --> 00:22:46.290
I mean really $1 a book for
localized publishing, it's a

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:47.880
very, very cost effective
solution.

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:50.780
And for us, it's not because
we're Luddites, but it's

00:22:50.780 --> 00:22:52.500
really because we're working
on some really deep

00:22:52.500 --> 00:22:55.160
foundational issues of
is a child literate?

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.030
Is a child going to be able
to learn to read?

00:22:57.030 --> 00:22:59.710
But once that happens, I think
what ends up happening is

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:01.640
those kids should
be the same as--

00:23:01.640 --> 00:23:02.840
I don't want to speak
for any of you.

00:23:02.840 --> 00:23:04.850
But I'm platform agnostic.

00:23:04.850 --> 00:23:05.840
I love to read books.

00:23:05.840 --> 00:23:07.110
I love to read magazines.

00:23:07.110 --> 00:23:09.490
If I'm going to long trip and
I'm going read the Steve Jobs'

00:23:09.490 --> 00:23:11.885
bio, I'm likely to actually put
it on my device because

00:23:11.885 --> 00:23:13.050
it's going to save me
from carrying around

00:23:13.050 --> 00:23:14.390
a seven pound book.

00:23:14.390 --> 00:23:17.680
But I think the key thing is
literacy, a habit of reading

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:20.220
from a young age, are
preconditions for any

00:23:20.220 --> 00:23:22.270
technology solutions to actually
be able to work.

00:23:22.270 --> 00:23:24.440
And just think about this for
yourself, if you hadn't gotten

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:27.540
literate at a young age, odds
are really strong you would

00:23:27.540 --> 00:23:29.650
not be working here.

00:23:29.650 --> 00:23:31.370
And I think we have to remind
the world of that [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:34.010 --> 00:23:37.210
Because I read you're
a tough interviewer.

00:23:37.210 --> 00:23:39.940
No, but I do want to say that
because I do want to remind

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:43.420
that 98% of the illiterate
people in the world today are

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:44.970
in the developing world.

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:47.010
And we haven't totally cracked
literacy in the developed

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:48.730
world, but we've come
really, really far.

00:23:48.730 --> 00:23:51.290
But in the developing world,
it's 49 our of 50 illiterate

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:54.230
people live in the
developing world.

