00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:14.720
So in the developing world, you
actually can't find the

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:16.480
equivalent of Dr. Seuss.

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:18.660
Because the for-profit
publishers don't want to

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:22.290
publish books for children in
languages where people live on

00:25:22.290 --> 00:25:23.610
less than $2 a day.

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:25.900
And if you have $2 in your
pocket, think about what if

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:30.320
that was all you had for food,
shelter, clothing, medicine.

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:30.810
That's it.

00:25:30.810 --> 00:25:32.330
You don't have anything
left over for books.

00:25:32.330 --> 00:25:34.460
So the for-profit publishers
don't publish children's

00:25:34.460 --> 00:25:39.040
literature in Nepalese, Khmer,
Lao, Zulu, Setswana, Xhosa,

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:42.120
Sinhalese, Tamil, [INAUDIBLE],
Rajasthani, Bengala.

00:25:42.120 --> 00:25:45.030
I gave you a really depressing
long list of languages.

00:25:45.030 --> 00:25:46.480
But this for me is like
where the supply

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:47.570
chain of poverty starts.

00:25:47.570 --> 00:25:50.120
Because if kids don't have books
in their mother tongue,

00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:51.336
how are they growing up literate
and how they going to

00:25:51.336 --> 00:25:52.570
grow up in a habit of reading?

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:55.110
We learned this because we
were talking about data

00:25:55.110 --> 00:25:57.880
collection, what gets
measured gets done.

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:01.190
In 2003, we went out and asked
our customers, we asked the

00:26:01.190 --> 00:26:02.870
little people, how
are we doing?

00:26:02.870 --> 00:26:04.850
What would cause you to
libraries more often?

00:26:04.850 --> 00:26:08.630
Would it be longer hours, open
at night, open on weekends?

00:26:08.630 --> 00:26:11.440
The number one answer kids gave
us, 52% of kids said more

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:12.950
books in the mother tongue.

00:26:12.950 --> 00:26:15.160
More books in Nepalese, more
books in Vietnamese.

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:17.520
Well, that sounds like a giant
no-brainer, of course they

00:26:17.520 --> 00:26:19.790
want books in the language
they speak at home.

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:22.650
But the for-profit publishers
don't publish because there's

00:26:22.650 --> 00:26:24.080
no profit incentive.

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:25.180
So we looked at the data.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:27.620
And at Room to Read,
we don't sit around

00:26:27.620 --> 00:26:29.290
and whinge or whine.

00:26:29.290 --> 00:26:31.620
We don't talk about problems.

00:26:31.620 --> 00:26:33.720
We act about solutions.

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:35.990
And so we went out to the Skoll
Foundation, and thank

00:26:35.990 --> 00:26:39.870
goodness Jeff Skoll has a team
and Sally Osberg have a team

00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:40.570
that takes risks.

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:44.440
They gave us $100,000 to go
search for Seuss, to go find

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:45.720
the Dr. Seuss or the Drs.

00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:47.960
Seuss, starting with Nepal, but

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:49.080
eventually in other languages.

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:51.780
And what we found was this
absolutely, incredibly

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:55.190
creative community that existed
in these countries,

00:26:55.190 --> 00:26:57.480
authors and artists with
story ideas, but

00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:00.560
nobody had ever asked.

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:02.680
We found a group called the
Nepalese Society for

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:04.210
Children's Literature.

00:27:04.210 --> 00:27:05.420
We don't know what the heck they
had been doing all those

00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:07.070
years because they hadn't been
producing much children's

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:08.730
literature.

00:27:08.730 --> 00:27:11.170
But we said, we have the money
to produce 10 books.

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:13.890
And within a month, our local
team in Nepal had 67

00:27:13.890 --> 00:27:15.320
manuscript ideas.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:18.350
So we already had a backlog
of manuscript ideas.

00:27:18.350 --> 00:27:21.640
And so we basically decided we
would become a publisher, not

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:23.050
on a for-profit basis.

00:27:23.050 --> 00:27:25.190
And the thing that we wanted
to do, we said it would be

00:27:25.190 --> 00:27:28.430
easier to just translate
existing children's books,

00:27:28.430 --> 00:27:31.840
like to just overlay some Khmer
script on "Clifford the

00:27:31.840 --> 00:27:34.850
Big Red Dog." But we decided
that we should actually do

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:35.820
original literature.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:37.960
Because what's the point of
having a book about the White

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:41.020
Christmas so that kids in Zambia
can be confused about

00:27:41.020 --> 00:27:43.400
caroling, and eggnog's,
and snowflakes.

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:46.390
Or have a book where mom drives
up in the Volvo station

00:27:46.390 --> 00:27:48.940
wagon to the suburban ranch home
and kids in Nepal like

00:27:48.940 --> 00:27:50.390
don't know what a suburban
home is.

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:52.820
And so we become a publisher
in local language.

00:27:52.820 --> 00:27:54.490
And those first 10 books,
from little

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:55.550
things, big things grow.

00:27:55.550 --> 00:27:58.790
We've now published 850
original titles.

00:27:58.790 --> 00:27:59.990
We're going to publish
our 1,000

00:27:59.990 --> 00:28:01.500
original title this year.

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:04.180
And it's local, local, local,
local authors, local artists,

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:06.260
local editors, and
local content.

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:08.180
Now, what's great about that
then is we also control the

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:09.470
printing presses.

00:28:09.470 --> 00:28:12.200
And it's literally
$1 per book.

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:14.250
So we even have like
10-year-olds, who for their

00:28:14.250 --> 00:28:16.200
birthday will say if everything
can give me $10,

00:28:16.200 --> 00:28:18.800
Room to Read can produce
100 book.

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:20.720
So the local area publishing
thing took off from that.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:21.270
And it's great.

00:28:21.270 --> 00:28:22.350
I tell a story in the book--

00:28:22.350 --> 00:28:24.620
did can you indulge me in
one more quick story?

00:28:24.620 --> 00:28:29.200
One of my favorite in the new
book is called "Baby Fish Goes

00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:32.590
to School." So if "Searching for
Seuss" as a chapter, was

00:28:32.590 --> 00:28:33.880
about the problem.

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:35.800
"Baby Fish Goes to School"
is a chapter where the

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:36.710
solution comes up.

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:39.290
And what happened is not just
adults wanted to write

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:41.420
children's books, but a lot of
the students came up to us and

00:28:41.420 --> 00:28:43.210
said they had story ideas.

00:28:43.210 --> 00:28:46.440
And so in Sri Lanka, two teenage
girls, 13 or 14 years

00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:48.920
old, came up the concept that
they wrote and illustrated,

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:50.610
called "Baby Fish
Goes to School."

00:28:50.610 --> 00:28:52.940
And it was all about a little
fish who lives in the pond.

00:28:52.940 --> 00:28:55.230
And every day watches the
animals walking along the side

00:28:55.230 --> 00:28:56.840
of the pond, going to school.

00:28:56.840 --> 00:28:58.890
He sticks his head above the
water and says, where you guys

00:28:58.890 --> 00:28:59.400
go every day?

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:00.590
And horse says, we
go to school.

00:29:00.590 --> 00:29:00.920
We love it.

00:29:00.920 --> 00:29:03.120
And the pig says, we sing
songs and play games.

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:05.080
And the chicken says,
we get to eat curry.

00:29:05.080 --> 00:29:07.280
And we get to dance and take
naps and read books.

00:29:07.280 --> 00:29:09.260
And Baby Fish is like wow,
that's fantastic.

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:10.700
I want to go to school.

00:29:10.700 --> 00:29:11.870
Well, that night it
tells mother.

00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:13.380
And the mother says, you
can't go to school.

00:29:13.380 --> 00:29:14.245
Why not?

00:29:14.245 --> 00:29:16.450
Well, the school is on land.

00:29:16.450 --> 00:29:19.200
And Baby Fish is like OK,
that totally sucks.

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:21.850
That's a loose translation
from Tamil language.

00:29:24.710 --> 00:29:28.020
But the animals thankfully are
action-oriented optimists.

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:29.060
They're not talking
about the problem.

00:29:29.060 --> 00:29:29.900
They're acting in
the solution.

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:32.820
They go out-- and maybe a bonus
point for anybody who

00:29:32.820 --> 00:29:35.239
guesses what they do?

